<br>
It's now up at Spacedaily. There's a link to us at the bottom of the page.<br>
<br>
I'm going to compose that article soon. I was already planning a critique of our opposition. Now I've a good reason to get started immediately. There's plenty of other material collected here so I plan to pick that apart aswell. We are not arguing that there is no risk associated with nuclear power. Nasa was falsely accused of having made that claim by GN in the past. I would argue that the risk is an acceptable one and the opposition has exagerrated it. Life is all about taking risks in the name of progress. Should cars be banned? Thousands die every year in automobile accidents. How is nuclear power going to get any safer if we aren't allowed to develop it? The toxicity implied by these luddites is ridiculous. They talk as if an accident would wipe out all life on Earth. In truth there is virtually no risk of even a single fatality. Plutonium would have to be ingested to cause harm. You are more likely to get a melanoma sitting out in the Sun than handling encased Plutonium. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=oberth>oberth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/27/03 11:41:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=156.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  article</span><hr size=1> Go get'em!!! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1889<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/27/03 12:36:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=156.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: article</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> In 1997 NASA launched the Cassini space probe carrying 72 pounds of plutonium that fortunately did not experience failure. If it had, hundreds of thousands of people around the world could have been contaminated.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
How can you cite a success as a failure?  This is true 'spin'.  Hundreds of thousands contaminated?  What is his risk mitigation source? <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Beyond accidents impacting the planet, the space nuclear production process at the DoE labs will lead to significant numbers of workers and communities being contaminated. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Beer is 13 times more radioactive than the cooling water discharged from a nuclear power plant.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Serious questions need to be asked: How will workers be protected? Where will they test the nuclear rocket? How much will it cost? What would be the impacts of a launch accidents?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
From everything that we've read to date, this is not a revival of the ROVER/NERVA nuclear thermal rocket program.  It is a simple nuclear reactor providing electricity for an ion engine.  The engine itself is not radioactive and can be easily bench tested as the Deep Space 1 ion engine was.  The reactor would provide the electricity for this ion engine after it has reached earth orbit.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Critics of NASA have long stated that... the NASA space nukes initiative represents the Bush administration's covert move to develop power systems for space-based weapons such as lasers on satellites. The military has often stated that their planned lasers in space will require enormous power projection capability and that nuclear reactors in orbit <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Wrong.  The military abandoned it's nuclear space reactor (SP-100) in the 80's.  Nothing covert or secretive about the military's space based reactor research or about SDI, it was in the news frequently   in the mid-late 80's.  This information is simply 20 years out of date.  I'm not familiar with any current plans to place a laser in space as  a weapon?  Anyone else know anything about this that is factual?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.fas.org/nuke/space/c06sdi_1.htm">www.fas.org/nuke/space/c06sdi_1.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>NASA's nuclear rocket is a Trojan horse for the militarization of space<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Technically it's assumed to be a reactor powered ion engine, not a nuclear rocket.  WE should quote how NASA is a civilan agency and differentiate it from the military...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>In the end hundreds and hundreds of billions of dollars will be wasted on plans for the nuclearization and weaponization of space.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
How does he know this?  Can the author provide a budget line item that has these figures?  No.  Because it's a flawed statement, an 'assumption'.  Perhaps a quote on the market value of one moderate sized iron ore asteroid would fit in here nicely?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Their plans now literally threaten the life of the entire planetary ecosystem.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
