<br>
Just before the launch of the (Galileo or Cassini), the LA Times did a large spread (front page plus 1 1/2 pages inside) about the &quot;hugh dangers&quot; associated with the launch of the nuclear RTG's inside.<br>
<br>
The whole tenor of the article was the usual - Fear. Why? Fear sells newspapers. <br>
 <br>
The quotes were the usual hysteria (&quot;If there's an accident, they'll have to evacuate all of southern Florida for thousands of years. It'll become as desolate as the face of the moon.&quot;). The &quot;experts&quot; were the same (John Gofman et al) - anyone who could stick a Dr or PhD alongside their name, and was willing to the most extreme comment about &quot;possible&quot; outcomes. Those estimates are generally delivered in the most useless of statistics - the single bounded limit. When some alarmist warns that &quot;up to one million people will die if there's an accident&quot;, it is useful to note that he is RIGHT. Zero and one are included in the subset of &quot;up to one million.&quot; It's just that the press is disinclined to ruin a perfectly good sound bite with such annoying little nicities.<br>
<br>
Back to the article. It was so riddled with nonsense that I called the paper and talked to the writer.  <br>
<br>
He first tried to disclaim responsibility in an interesting way. &quot;I'm not the science writer. I was just filling in for him.&quot; Well, duh.<br>
<br>
I asked him if he had bothered to check these facts with anyone. (We were specifically talking about the &quot;...evacuate south Florida...&quot; comment above.) He assured me that Dr. Gofman had validated his facts. After assuring him that Bozo the clown has approximately equivalent levels of rigor, but tons more objectivity, I pointed out that we've already run that experiment. It's called Nagasaki (specifically for Pu) and Hiroshima (for U). And Nevada. <br>
<br>
I pointed out that, when a fission bomb goes off, only about 1% of the matter gets turned into energy. The other 99% gets scattered about. Certainly much of it upward, but also downward and to either side of the epicenter. <br>
<br>
The upshot of all of this is that, neither city (nor surrounding 1000's of square miles) needed to be evacuated for 1000's of years. They are both beautiful, rebuilt cities with continuous, healthy populations from that day to the present. <br>
<br>
And as a side note, both cities have slightly (but easily measured) elevated levels of background radiation to this day. 50 years worth of BEIR studies (Biological Effects of Ionizing Radiation)** and RERF (Radiation  Effects  Research  Foundation) shows that, while people exposed to primary radiation from the blast suffered severe and occasionally fatal radiation sickness, those exposed only to secondary and background radiation have zero measurable elevated levels of the usual litany of cancers, leukemias, birth defects, etc. compared with the rest of Japan over these years. <br>
<br>
The Times writer's response was instructive. He said &quot;Oh.&quot; Great. I gave him the name of a couple of real experts to call. And then told him I'd be anxious to see his published corrections. Needless to say, that article never appeared.<br>
<br>
This argument, by the way, applies equally to the non-issue of &quot;dirty bombs&quot; that is currently receiving so much hyperventilation in the news. One of these devices (a radioisotope, most likely U or Pu) surrounding a chemical explosive will scatter pieces of the radioactive material around. The first observation is that you go around and pick up the pieces and stick them into a container. The pieces are very easy to find (with a Gieger counter), U and Pu are predominantly alpha and beta emitters, so pick 'em up with tweezers and stick 'em in a container, and go back to your normal life. <br>
<br>
In a dirty bomb, there would be no primary radiation (the initial pulse of gamma radiation that cause of all the radiation effects seen in those cities), there would be no secondary radiation (caused by the irradiation of materials by the primary radiation pulse). Even if there were no cleanup after one of these bombs exploded (impossible to imagine), there would background radiation less than what has existed in Nagasaki for 50 years. And there were no measurable effects from this background radiation.<br>
<br>
The operationally important point is that, if the print and televised media would actually tell the truth about these issues, it would substantially decrease the chance that some terrorist will actually do this. Continuing to pander to fear and hyping the effects actually encourages some bozo to employ such a weapon. <br>
<br>
-tfk<br>
